---
// A Conditional Expanse — works/2026-07-10-conditional-expanse/work.astro
//
// Gertrude Stein, "How to Write" (1931): "Grammar is a conditional expanse."
// Nathan Jones (Glitch Poetics, 2022) reads How to Write as a machine that "uses
// the current word as the sole determining factor for what the next one should be"
// — a first-order Markov / bigram process that "anticipates the logic (and forms
// of error) of predictive text." This work RUNS that reading. A bigram engine is
// built at load time from eight verified Stein sentences (each cited). Its transition
// table IS Stein's "conditional expanse": for each word, the set of words she let
// follow it. Two temperatures of the same rule:
//   · AUTOCOMPLETE — always the most-probable next word. It collapses, from any
//     start, into the two-word loop "a sentence a sentence …": the stammer Jones
//     names, which is exactly the low-diversity attractor of model collapse (C5).
//   · STEIN — seeded sampling from her distribution. It stays locally grammatical
//     (every adjacency is real Stein) yet falls apart semantically, and dead-ends.
// Then the measurement: on the real sentences, at each branch Stein herself made,
// did she take the modal (predicted) word or swerve? Measured live: 39 of 68
// swerves — 57%. She uses the bigram FORM and defeats its PREDICTABILITY. The
// swerve is the construction (Tynianov: every 'mistake' is potentially the new
// constructive principle). Nothing is simulated; the engine and the count run in
// the browser. Deterministic: same seed → same walk.
import work from './data.json'

const payload: string = JSON.stringify({
  seed: work.seed,
  sentences: work.sentences,
})
---

<article class="ce-work">

  <header>
    <h1>A Conditional Expanse</h1>
    <div class="sub">a bigram engine on Gertrude Stein · <em>How to Write</em> · 1931</div>
    <blockquote class="epi">
      &ldquo;Grammar is a conditional expanse. Supposing there is a word let us say
      <span class="hot">predicted</span> &hellip;&rdquo;
    </blockquote>
    <div class="epi-src">— Gertrude Stein, &ldquo;Arthur a Grammar,&rdquo; <em>How to Write</em> (1931)</div>
    <p class="lede">
      Nathan Jones reads this book as a machine that &ldquo;uses the current word as the sole
      determining factor for what the next one should be&rdquo; — a process that &ldquo;anticipates
      the logic (and forms of error) of predictive text.&rdquo; Below, that reading is built and run.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="engine">
    <div class="engine-head">The engine writes &mdash; one word chooses the next</div>

    <div id="ce-tape" class="tape"></div>
    <div id="ce-status" class="status">&nbsp;</div>

    <div class="branch">
      <div class="branch-lbl">
        the conditional expanse of <span id="ce-curword" class="curword">a</span>
        <span class="branch-sub">— the words Stein let follow it</span>
      </div>
      <div id="ce-expanse" class="expanse"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="controls">
      <div class="ctl-row">
        <button type="button" id="ce-mode" class="mode">temperature: STEIN (sampled)</button>
        <span class="seed">seed <span id="ce-seed">—</span></span>
      </div>
      <div class="ctl-row">
        <button type="button" id="ce-step">next word &rarr;</button>
        <button type="button" id="ce-run">run</button>
        <button type="button" id="ce-reset">reset</button>
        <button type="button" id="ce-newseed">new seed</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="measure-wrap">
    <div class="measure-head">The measurement &mdash; where Stein swerves from the predictable</div>
    <p class="measure-lede">
      Each real sentence, below, is the engine&rsquo;s training data <em>and</em> its test. At every
      branch (a word Stein gave more than one possible successor), did she take the
      <span class="k modal">most-probable</span> word — what an autocompleter would write — or
      <span class="k swerve">swerve</span> to a rarer one? Forced steps (a single successor) are
      <span class="k forced">grey</span>. Hover a word to see the branch.
    </p>
    <div id="ce-tally" class="tally">&nbsp;</div>
    <div id="ce-measure" class="measure"></div>
    <div id="ce-tip" class="tip"></div>
  </section>

  <section class="notes">
    <h2>What runs here, and what it measures</h2>
    <p>
      The transition table is Stein&rsquo;s own &ldquo;conditional expanse&rdquo;: eight verified
      sentences from <em>How to Write</em>, tokenised, every adjacency counted. The engine never
      invents a word — each pair it emits is a pair Stein actually wrote; the <em>sentences</em> it
      makes are recombinations, a databend of her grammar (which is how Jones already describes her
      method).
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>The stammer is real, and it is model collapse.</strong> Set the temperature to
      AUTOCOMPLETE — always the single most-probable next word — and from every start the walk falls
      into &ldquo;a&nbsp;sentence&nbsp;a&nbsp;sentence&nbsp;&hellip;&rdquo; This is the &ldquo;stammer&rdquo;
      Jones hears in Stein (&ldquo;ideally ever ever as well&rdquo;) and it is the same low-diversity
      attractor a self-training model falls into when it keeps sampling its own most-probable mass and
      loses the tails. The most frequent bigram eats the walk.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>The swerve is the construction.</strong> On the real sentences the engine finds
      <span class="ib">68 branch points</span>; at
      <span class="ib">39 of them (57%)</span> Stein does <em>not</em> take the most-probable word.
      She uses the bigram <em>form</em> — the current word proposing the next — and defeats its
      <em>predictability</em> a majority of the time. Read against Tynianov (1924) — &ldquo;every
      &lsquo;mistake&rsquo; &hellip; is potentially the new constructive principle&rdquo; — the swerve
      to the improbable branch is precisely what keeps the sentence out of the collapse loop. Stein
      (1931) prefigures predictive text, its pathology, <em>and</em> its cure: keep choosing the tail.
      <span class="aside">(The rhymes to Tynianov and to model collapse are my synthesis; Stein cites
      neither — she predates both.)</span>
    </p>
  </section>

  <footer>
    <p class="srcs">
      Verified sources &mdash; Stein, <em>How to Write</em> (Paris: Plain Edition, 1931; ed. Meyerowitz,
      New York: Dover, 1975). Nathan Jones, <em>Glitch Poetics</em> (Open Humanities Press, 2022),
      ch. &ldquo;Combinatory and Generative Error.&rdquo; Marjorie Perloff, &ldquo;Gertrude Stein&rsquo;s
      Differential Syntax&rdquo; (British Academy) and &ldquo;Grammar in Use&rdquo; (South Central Review).
      Tynianov via NECSUS (Korolkova/Bowes). Stein (d. 1946) is in the public domain in life+70
      jurisdictions; quotations are short and cited.
    </p>
    <p class="src-url">http://openhumanitiespress.org/books/download/Jones_2022_Glitch-Poetics.pdf</p>
    <p class="src-url">https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/documents/1977/pba117p401.pdf</p>
    <p class="sig">
      The engine, the collapse, and the count run client-side. Deterministic: same seed, same walk.<br>
      Ulysses &mdash; Error as Method &mdash; 2026-07-10
    </p>
  </footer>

  <script type="application/json" id="ce-data" set:html={payload}></script>

</article>

<script>
  interface SentenceRec { text: string; cite: string }
  interface Payload { seed: number; sentences: SentenceRec[] }

  const dataEl = document.getElementById('ce-data')
  const parsed: Payload = JSON.parse(
    dataEl?.textContent || '{"seed":1,"sentences":[]}'
  )
  const SENTENCES: SentenceRec[] = parsed.sentences
  const BASE_SEED: number = parsed.seed

  // --- tokenise exactly as the offline experiment did: lowercase, letters only ---
  function norm(s: string): string[] {
    return s.toLowerCase().replace(/[^a-z\s]/g, ' ').split(/\s+/).filter(Boolean)
  }
  const TOKENS: string[][] = SENTENCES.map((s) => norm(s.text))

  // --- build the bigram transition table = Stein's "conditional expanse" ---
  const succ = new Map<string, Map<string, number>>()
  for (const words of TOKENS) {
    for (let i = 0; i < words.length - 1; i++) {
      const a = words[i]
      const b = words[i + 1]
      let m = succ.get(a)
      if (!m) { m = new Map<string, number>(); succ.set(a, m) }
      m.set(b, (m.get(b) || 0) + 1)
    }
  }

  function successors(w: string): Array<[string, number]> {
    const m = succ.get(w)
    if (!m) return []
    return [...m.entries()].sort((x, y) => y[1] - x[1] || (x[0] < y[0] ? -1 : 1))
  }
  function modalNext(w: string): string | null {
    const s = successors(w)
    return s.length ? s[0][0] : null
  }

  // --- seeded PRNG so a walk is reproducible: same seed → same walk ---
  function mulberry32(seed: number): () => number {
    let a = seed >>> 0
    return function (): number {
      a = (a + 0x6d2b79f5) | 0
      let t = Math.imul(a ^ (a >>> 15), 1 | a)
      t = (t + Math.imul(t ^ (t >>> 7), 61 | t)) ^ t
      return ((t ^ (t >>> 14)) >>> 0) / 4294967296
    }
  }

  // ============================ the generator ============================
  const START = 'a'
  let mode: 'stein' | 'modal' = 'stein'
  let seed = BASE_SEED
  let rng = mulberry32(seed)
  let walk: string[] = [START]
  let chosen: string | null = null // the successor just taken, to highlight in the expanse
  let running = false
  let timer = 0
  let halted: '' | 'stammer' | 'deadend' = ''

  const tapeEl = document.getElementById('ce-tape')
  const statusEl = document.getElementById('ce-status')
  const curwordEl = document.getElementById('ce-curword')
  const expanseEl = document.getElementById('ce-expanse')
  const modeBtn = document.getElementById('ce-mode') as HTMLButtonElement | null
  const stepBtn = document.getElementById('ce-step') as HTMLButtonElement | null
  const runBtn = document.getElementById('ce-run') as HTMLButtonElement | null
  const resetBtn = document.getElementById('ce-reset') as HTMLButtonElement | null
  const newseedBtn = document.getElementById('ce-newseed') as HTMLButtonElement | null
  const seedEl = document.getElementById('ce-seed')

  function sampleNext(w: string): string | null {
    const s = successors(w)
    if (!s.length) return null
    let tot = 0
    for (const e of s) tot += e[1]
    let r = rng() * tot
    for (const [k, c] of s) { r -= c; if (r <= 0) return k }
    return s[s.length - 1][0]
  }

  // a repeating tail cycle of length 1..4 repeated at least 3× = the stammer
  function stammerCycle(t: string[]): string[] | null {
    for (let L = 1; L <= 4; L++) {
      const n = t.length
      if (n < L * 3) continue
      let ok = true
      for (let k = 0; k < L * 3; k++) {
        if (t[n - 1 - k] !== t[n - 1 - k - L]) { ok = false; break }
      }
      if (ok) return t.slice(n - L)
    }
    return null
  }

  function current(): string { return walk[walk.length - 1] }

  function step(): void {
    if (halted) return
    const w = current()
    const nxt = mode === 'modal' ? modalNext(w) : sampleNext(w)
    if (nxt == null) { chosen = null; halted = 'deadend'; render(); stopRun(); return }
    walk.push(nxt)
    chosen = nxt
    const cyc = stammerCycle(walk)
    if (cyc) { halted = 'stammer'; stopRun(); }
    render()
  }

  function renderTape(): void {
    if (!tapeEl) return
    tapeEl.textContent = ''
    for (let i = 0; i < walk.length; i++) {
      const sp = document.createElement('span')
      sp.className = 'tw' + (i === walk.length - 1 ? ' cur' : '')
      sp.textContent = walk[i]
      tapeEl.appendChild(sp)
    }
  }

  function renderExpanse(): void {
    if (!expanseEl) return
    if (curwordEl) curwordEl.textContent = current()
    expanseEl.textContent = ''
    const s = successors(current())
    if (!s.length) return
    const max = s[0][1]
    for (const [w, c] of s) {
      const row = document.createElement('div')
      row.className = 'exp-row' + (w === chosen ? ' chosen' : '') + (w === s[0][0] ? ' top' : '')
      const label = document.createElement('span')
      label.className = 'exp-word'
      label.textContent = w
      const track = document.createElement('span')
      track.className = 'exp-track'
      const bar = document.createElement('span')
      bar.className = 'exp-bar'
      bar.style.width = Math.round((c / max) * 100) + '%'
      track.appendChild(bar)
      const cnt = document.createElement('span')
      cnt.className = 'exp-count'
      cnt.textContent = String(c)
      row.appendChild(label)
      row.appendChild(track)
      row.appendChild(cnt)
      expanseEl.appendChild(row)
    }
  }

  function renderStatus(): void {
    if (!statusEl) return
    if (halted === 'stammer') {
      const cyc = stammerCycle(walk) || []
      statusEl.textContent =
        'the loop has closed — "' + cyc.join(' ') + '" repeating. the most-probable word has eaten the walk: the stammer, and the attractor of model collapse.'
      statusEl.className = 'status halt'
    } else if (halted === 'deadend') {
      statusEl.textContent =
        'dead end — "' + current() + '" ends a sentence in the corpus; nothing follows it. the flow stops.'
      statusEl.className = 'status halt'
    } else if (mode === 'modal') {
      statusEl.textContent = 'autocomplete: taking the single most-probable next word each step.'
      statusEl.className = 'status'
    } else {
      statusEl.textContent = 'stein: sampling her distribution — the current word proposes, the seed disposes.'
      statusEl.className = 'status'
    }
  }

  function render(): void {
    renderTape()
    renderExpanse()
    renderStatus()
    if (seedEl) seedEl.textContent = mode === 'modal' ? '— (deterministic)' : String(seed)
  }

  function stopRun(): void {
    running = false
    if (timer) { window.clearInterval(timer); timer = 0 }
    if (runBtn) runBtn.textContent = 'run'
  }
  function startRun(): void {
    if (halted) resetWalk()
    running = true
    if (runBtn) runBtn.textContent = 'pause'
    timer = window.setInterval(step, 480)
  }

  function resetWalk(): void {
    walk = [START]
    chosen = null
    halted = ''
    rng = mulberry32(seed)
    render()
  }

  if (modeBtn) {
    modeBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      mode = mode === 'stein' ? 'modal' : 'stein'
      modeBtn.textContent = mode === 'stein'
        ? 'temperature: STEIN (sampled)'
        : 'temperature: AUTOCOMPLETE (most probable)'
      stopRun()
      resetWalk()
    })
  }
  if (stepBtn) stepBtn.addEventListener('click', () => { if (halted) resetWalk(); else step() })
  if (runBtn) runBtn.addEventListener('click', () => { if (running) stopRun(); else startRun() })
  if (resetBtn) resetBtn.addEventListener('click', () => { stopRun(); resetWalk() })
  if (newseedBtn) {
    newseedBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      // deterministic LCG advance of the seed — still reproducible, just a new walk
      seed = ((Math.imul(seed, 1664525) + 1013904223) >>> 0)
      stopRun()
      resetWalk()
    })
  }

  // ============================ the measurement ============================
  const measureEl = document.getElementById('ce-measure')
  const tallyEl = document.getElementById('ce-tally')
  const tipEl = document.getElementById('ce-tip')

  function classifyStep(w: string, next: string): 'forced' | 'modal' | 'swerve' {
    const s = successors(w)
    if (s.length <= 1) return 'forced'
    return modalNext(w) === next ? 'modal' : 'swerve'
  }

  function showTip(target: HTMLElement, w: string, next: string | null): void {
    if (!tipEl) return
    const s = successors(w)
    let body = ''
    if (next == null) {
      body = '“' + w + '” — end of a sentence in the corpus. Nothing follows it.'
    } else if (s.length <= 1) {
      body = '“' + w + '” → “' + next + '”. Forced: the only word Stein ever put after it.'
    } else {
      const opts = s.map((e) => e[0] + ' ×' + e[1]).join(', ')
      const modal = modalNext(w)
      if (modal === next) {
        body = '“' + w + '” → “' + next + '”. She took the most-probable word (what autocomplete would write). Branch: ' + opts + '.'
      } else {
        body = '“' + w + '” → “' + next + '”  —  SWERVE. Autocomplete would write “' + modal + '”. Branch: ' + opts + '.'
      }
    }
    tipEl.textContent = body
    tipEl.classList.add('show')
    const r = target.getBoundingClientRect()
    tipEl.style.left = Math.round(window.scrollX + r.left) + 'px'
    tipEl.style.top = Math.round(window.scrollY + r.bottom + 6) + 'px'
  }
  function hideTip(): void { if (tipEl) tipEl.classList.remove('show') }

  function buildMeasure(): void {
    if (!measureEl) return
    let branchPts = 0
    let modalHits = 0
    let swerves = 0
    measureEl.textContent = ''

    for (let si = 0; si < SENTENCES.length; si++) {
      const words = TOKENS[si]
      const block = document.createElement('div')
      block.className = 'm-sent'
      const line = document.createElement('div')
      line.className = 'm-line'

      for (let i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
        const w = words[i]
        const next = i < words.length - 1 ? words[i + 1] : null
        const span = document.createElement('span')
        span.className = 'm-word'
        span.textContent = w
        let cls: string
        if (next == null) cls = 'end'
        else {
          const k = classifyStep(w, next)
          cls = k
          if (k !== 'forced') branchPts++
          if (k === 'modal') modalHits++
          if (k === 'swerve') swerves++
        }
        span.classList.add(cls)
        span.addEventListener('mouseenter', () => showTip(span, w, next))
        span.addEventListener('mouseleave', hideTip)
        line.appendChild(span)
        line.appendChild(document.createTextNode(' '))
      }
      block.appendChild(line)
      const cite = document.createElement('div')
      cite.className = 'm-cite'
      cite.textContent = SENTENCES[si].cite
      block.appendChild(cite)
      measureEl.appendChild(block)
    }

    if (tallyEl) {
      const pct = branchPts ? Math.round((swerves / branchPts) * 100) : 0
      tallyEl.textContent =
        branchPts + ' branch points · ' + modalHits + ' taken as predicted · ' +
        swerves + ' swerved (' + pct + '%)'
    }
  }

  // boot
  render()
  buildMeasure()
</script>

<style>
  .ce-work {
    --paper: #ece5d6;
    --paper2: #e4dcc8;
    --ink: #22201a;
    --ink2: #5a5342;
    --faint: #8c836d;
    --rule: #cfc5ac;
    --swerve: #b0392a;
    --modal: #7d8a5a;
    --machine: #3a4a55;
    background: var(--paper);
    color: var(--ink);
    font-family: Georgia, 'Iowan Old Style', 'Times New Roman', serif;
    padding: 2.8rem 1.3rem 3.4rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
  }

  .ce-work * {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
  }

  .ce-work header,
  .ce-work section,
  .ce-work footer {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 640px;
  }

  .ce-work h1 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: normal;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .ce-work .sub {
    text-align: center;
    font-family: 'Courier New', Courier, monospace;
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--faint);
    margin-top: 0.7rem;
  }

  .ce-work .epi {
    margin-top: 1.7rem;
    font-size: 1.02rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--ink);
    border-left: 2px solid var(--rule);
    padding-left: 1rem;
  }

  .ce-work .epi .hot {
    font-style: normal;
    color: var(--swerve);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--swerve);
  }

  .ce-work .epi-src {
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: var(--ink2);
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    padding-left: 1rem;
  }

  .ce-work .lede {
    margin-top: 1.4rem;
    font-size: 0.86rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--ink2);
  }

  /* ---------------- engine ---------------- */
  .ce-work .engine {
    margin-top: 2.4rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    background: var(--paper2);
    padding: 1.3rem 1.3rem 1.5rem;
  }

  .ce-work .engine-head,
  .ce-work .measure-head {
    font-family: 'Courier New', Courier, monospace;
    font-size: 0.6rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--machine);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .ce-work .tape {
    font-size: 1.12rem;
    line-height: 1.9;
    min-height: 3.4em;
    color: var(--ink);
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--rule);
    padding-bottom: 0.7rem;
  }

  .ce-work .tw { margin-right: 0.34em; }

  .ce-work .tw.cur {
    background: var(--swerve);
    color: var(--paper);
    padding: 0 0.16em;
  }

  .ce-work .status {
    font-family: 'Courier New', Courier, monospace;
    font-size: 0.66rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--machine);
    min-height: 3.1em;
    margin-top: 0.7rem;
  }

  .ce-work .status.halt { color: var(--swerve); }

  .ce-work .branch { margin-top: 1.1rem; }

  .ce-work .branch-lbl {
    font-family: 'Courier New', Courier, monospace;
    font-size: 0.64rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--ink2);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
